  <!-- Content -->
  <div class="blog-content">

    <p>
      Storm damage roof claims are the most common homeowners insurance claim in Utah — and one
      of the most frequently underpaid. The process isn't complicated, but there are specific steps
      that determine whether you recover the full cost of your repair or leave thousands of dollars
      on the table. This guide walks through the entire process, from documenting the damage to
      collecting the final check.
    </p>

    <div class="callout success">
      <p><strong>The most important thing:</strong> Get a licensed contractor's damage assessment before the insurance adjuster visits. Not after. Before. It's the single biggest factor in whether a claim pays out correctly.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What Utah Homeowners Insurance Covers (and Doesn't)</h2>

    <h3>Covered</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Hail damage to shingles, flashing, and roof structure</li>
      <li>Wind damage — blown-off shingles, lifted sections</li>
      <li>Falling trees or branches that damage the roof</li>
      <li>Ice dam damage (water backing up under shingles in winter)</li>
      <li>Fire or lightning damage</li>
      <li>Emergency repairs and tarping to prevent further damage</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Not Covered (Standard Policies)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Normal wear and tear — shingles that have simply aged out</li>
      <li>Gradual deterioration or lack of maintenance</li>
      <li>Improper original installation</li>
      <li>Cosmetic damage only (damage that doesn't affect function)</li>
      <li>Flood damage (requires separate flood insurance)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout warning">
      <p><strong>The age issue:</strong> Some Utah insurers are moving to ACV-only policies on older roofs — meaning they pay depreciated value only, with no replacement cost recovery. Check your policy declarations page. If it says "ACV roof" or your roof is over 20 years old, you may have a coverage gap worth addressing before the next storm season.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Step-by-Step Claims Process</h2>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">1</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>Document the Damage Before Calling Your Insurer</h3>
        <p>
          Take photos immediately after the storm — ground level first (gutters, downspouts, AC unit,
          window screens), then request a contractor inspection for roof-level documentation. Note the
          date of the storm and save any weather alerts, hail reports, or news coverage confirming the
          event in your area. This evidence establishes that the damage is storm-related, not pre-existing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">2</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>Get a Contractor's Damage Assessment</h3>
        <p>
          Call a licensed roofing contractor for a damage inspection before you file your claim.
          A contractor experienced with insurance work will document hail impact marks, measure affected
          square footage, photograph damage at the right angles, and produce a written assessment.
          This report is your strongest asset going into the adjuster visit. Most contractors who do
          insurance work offer this inspection for free.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">3</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>File Your Claim</h3>
        <p>
          Contact your insurer's claims line (not your agent — the claims department directly) and
          report the damage. Provide the storm date, your claim documentation, and the contractor's
          assessment if you have it. Get a claim number. The insurer will schedule an adjuster visit —
          typically within 1–2 weeks of filing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">4</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>Be Present for the Adjuster Visit — With Your Contractor</h3>
        <p>
          Adjusters work quickly and can miss damage. Having your contractor present during the
          adjuster visit is strongly recommended. They can point out specific damage the adjuster
          might overlook, answer technical questions, and ensure the written scope of damage is
          complete. An undocumented item at this stage won't be covered later.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">5</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>Review the Settlement Offer</h3>
        <p>
          The insurer will send an Estimate of Loss showing what they're covering. Review it with
          your contractor. Common issues: the scope underestimates damage (common with hail),
          labor rates are below current market, or depreciation was applied incorrectly. If the
          estimate doesn't match your contractor's assessment, you have the right to dispute it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="process-step">
      <div class="process-step__num">6</div>
      <div class="process-step__content">
        <h3>Complete the Work and Collect Recoverable Depreciation</h3>
        <p>
          Once the repair is completed, provide your insurer with the final paid invoice. If your
          policy has RCV (Replacement Cost Value) coverage, the withheld depreciation is now
          released — this is often a significant check. Don't close the claim until you've
          collected the RCV payment. Many homeowners leave this money uncollected.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Understanding ACV vs. RCV: Where Homeowners Get Underpaid</h2>

    <p>
      This is the most misunderstood part of a roof insurance claim in Utah.
    </p>

    <table class="comparison-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Payment Type</th>
          <th>What It Pays</th>
          <th>When You Get It</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>ACV (Actual Cash Value)</strong></td>
          <td>Replacement cost minus depreciation (age, condition, life expectancy)</td>
          <td>Initial check after adjuster approval</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Recoverable Depreciation</strong></td>
          <td>The withheld portion — the gap between ACV and full replacement cost</td>
          <td>After the repair is completed and documented</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>RCV (Full Replacement Cost)</strong></td>
          <td>ACV + Recoverable Depreciation = full replacement cost</td>
          <td>ACV upfront + depreciation released after completion</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> Your 15-year-old roof needs a $15,000 replacement. The insurer calculates 40% depreciation — so the ACV payment is $9,000. After you complete the repair and submit the invoice, they release the $6,000 in recoverable depreciation. Total collected: $15,000 minus your deductible. But you have to ask for and document that second payment.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What to Do If Your Claim Is Denied</h2>

    <p>
      A denial isn't final. Most Utah homeowners insurance policies include an appraisal or
      dispute resolution process for claim disagreements. The key steps:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Request the denial in writing with the specific reason cited</li>
      <li>Have your contractor document why they believe the damage is storm-related</li>
      <li>Invoke the appraisal clause in your policy — both you and the insurer hire an independent appraiser, and a neutral umpire resolves any disagreement</li>
      <li>Consider a public adjuster if the amount in dispute is significant (they work on contingency)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Many initial denials on Utah storm damage claims are reversed when the homeowner pushes back
      with proper documentation. Don't accept a denial without understanding the specific reason
      and whether it can be challenged.
    </p>

    <h2>Working With Insurance Claims in Sandy &amp; Salt Lake County</h2>
    <p>
      We work with homeowners throughout <a href="/areas/sandy">Sandy</a>, <a href="/areas/draper">Draper</a>,
      <a href="/areas/south-jordan">South Jordan</a>, <a href="/areas/murray">Murray</a>,
      <a href="/areas/midvale">Midvale</a>, <a href="/areas/west-jordan">West Jordan</a>,
      Cottonwood Heights, Herriman, Riverton, and <a href="/areas/salt-lake-city">Salt Lake City</a>
      to document storm damage and support the claims process. Free inspection, no pressure.
      If there's no covered damage, we'll tell you that too.
    </p>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How long do I have to file a roof insurance claim in Utah?</h3>
      <p>Most Utah policies require filing within 12 months of the damage event, though some policies have shorter windows. Check the "duties after loss" section of your policy for the exact deadline.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What documentation do I need for a roof insurance claim in Utah?</h3>
      <p>Photos of ground-level damage indicators (gutters, AC unit), date of the storm, your policy number, and a licensed contractor's written damage assessment with photos and measurements. Weather data showing the storm event in your area also helps.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What is the difference between ACV and RCV in a roof insurance claim?</h3>
      <p>ACV (Actual Cash Value) pays the depreciated value of your roof. RCV (Replacement Cost Value) policies pay ACV upfront, then release the withheld depreciation once the repair is completed and documented. Most Utah homeowners have RCV coverage — you just have to collect the second payment after the work is done.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Can an insurance company deny a roof claim in Utah?</h3>
      <p>Yes, but denials can be disputed. Common denial reasons: damage attributed to wear and tear, missing the filing deadline, or insufficient documentation. Request the denial in writing, have your contractor document storm causation, and invoke your policy's appraisal clause if needed.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Should I file an insurance claim before or after getting a contractor estimate?</h3>
      <p>Get the contractor estimate first. A contractor's damage assessment strengthens your claim and ensures the adjuster has the full scope of damage on the table from the start. Filing without documentation often results in an incomplete scope and a lower initial settlement offer.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="blog-cta">
      <h2>Need Storm Damage Documentation for Your Claim?</h2>
      <p>We provide free roof inspections with full damage documentation throughout Salt Lake County. Our contractors know what insurance adjusters need to see — and they'll be there with you.</p>
      <a href="/#get-estimate" class="btn btn--accent btn--lg">Request a Free Inspection</a>
      <br/><br/>
      <a href={phoneHref} style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.85); font-size: 1.05rem;">Or call now: {phone}</a>
    </div>

  </div>

